post_text:
NEW UPDATE: If your child is absent from school, we ask that you please call the office that day. With the COVID regulations, we cannot allow the student to return to school until we know the reason why they are out. Even if you are taking them to an appointment, please call us and let us know because until we have the conversation with a parent, we have no idea why your child is out. For the elementary school, please dial ext. 1401. For the high school, ext. 2400

Thank you for your patience and consideration.

post_text:
We want to thank all of our elementary parents this morning for a very successful drop off. Although it looks a different and a little chaotic, we will get the hang of it. Your patience was extremely appreciated.

Just a friendly reminder that for your safety, please do not park on the inner part of the drop-off loop. We do not want our parents and children having to cross in front of moving vehicles. In addition, we cannot have vehicles parked at the mouth of the driveway. It causes a back up into Greenwood Street and creates a potential head on situation for vehicles coming into the loop and exiting the loop.

post_text:
Wednesday, the New York Council of School Superintendents (NYSCOSS) released a statement regarding a letter they had written to the Governor asking to delay sports until January. The local media reports made it sound as if all NY Superintendents were on board. I can assure you that not only did this letter take me by surprise, but MANY Superintendents across our region and the state too. I was never asked of my opinion and my opinion does not reflect that of NYSCOSS.

Thomas J. Crook
Superintendent
text:
Wednesday, the New York Council of School Superintendents (NYSCOSS) released a statement regarding a letter they had written to the Governor asking to delay sports until January. The local media reports made it sound as if all NY Superintendents were on board. I can assure you that not only did this letter take me by surprise, but MANY Superintendents across our region and the state too. I was never asked of my opinion and my opinion does not reflect that of NYSCOSS.

Thomas J. Crook
Superintendent

post_text: Pro-Action's Summer Youth Employment Program applications are now available. The program is available to youth between the ages of 14-20 to provide a summer work experience at various work sites throughout Steuben County. Typically it is a 24-32 hour work week, paying minimum wage ($11.80). Please complete the application on our website at www.cgcsd.org and either return directly to Pro-Action using the contact information on the application or return to the HS guidance office no later than Thursday, July 16th.

Canisteo-Greenwood Central School
July 1 at 1:39 PM ·

We are pleased to announce the summer food program will resume Monday, July 6th-August 14th. C-G residents with children will be able to pick up food daily (M-F) from 9:00am - 10:30am at the Canisteo-Greenwood Elementary School. Drive up (or walk up) to the front entrance and a staff member will give you the food you need for the day (breakfast and lunch) per child in your household. Please remember face masks and social distancing applies. Thank you!

ATTENTION PARENTS!!!

This summer the Wimodaughsian Library is trying a new on-line summer reading program called Read Squared. Starting July 6 children aged 3 to 12 can register their reading minutes, and the first 15 minutes of reading each week means a choice of free ice cream from Annie’s, free pizza from Robbie’s, or free candy from Urban Rustique. You can read up to 2 hours each week and receive raffle tickets to win our grand prize in August, which is a stars and moon nightlight. There are also games to play. Here is the link: http://wimodaughsianny14.readsquared.com/ Check it out!

post_text:
Here is another weekly SEL (Social Emotional Learning) Activity from Mrs. Valentine and Mrs. Scott from CGES. Remember staying emotionally strong and healthy is just as important as staying academically strong and healthy.

This week, let’s focus on gratitude! It is important to think about people/things we appreciate during this tough time. Make someone's day by letting them know how much you care!

What can you do:
* Write someone a letter telling them why you appreciate them
* Draw a picture for someone special to you
* Reach out to someone with a positive message
* Play gratitude Tic Tac Toe

Some books related to gratitude:
Those Shoes by Maribeth Boelts https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_hVw1A9ekI8

Good People Everywhere by Lynea Gillen https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XFTw3EWlJd0

Kindness Starts with You by Jacquelyn Stagg https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w7DEAGINE_g

A Chair for My Mother by Vera B. Williams https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5ee44EjEwEU

Enjoy!
Mrs. Valentine and Mrs. Scott

We would like to take this opportunity to acknowledge our fantastic teachers. We do this any year, but this year is "special". You were thrown into the unknown with little time to prepare and have exceeded our expectations as a district. You have shown resiliency, tenacity, flexibility, compassion, and the list goes on and on. Everyone here on the administrative team wants to thank you for everything you do for our students and the community. You are the glue that holds us together, but it took something like this for us to find out that you are "super glue". Happy Teacher Appreciation Day!

We recently added some additional resources for our parents on the website. Please visit Headlines for material in how to deal with the mental and emotional state of our students as well as the parents. We are all dealing with extremely stressful times and taking care of ourselves and our students is paramount to a successful return to school.

https://www.cgcsd.org/cms/lib/NY19000576/Centricity/Domain/1/supportingchildren-covid-factsheet.pdf

If you have any concerns and would like to discuss it with someone, please contact the school either through telephone (if there is no answer, please leave a message) or email. We will make sure someone follows up with you. There are also many resources provided by the county. Their 211 helpline will provide you with the assistance you may need.

Please take care of yourselves and stay healthy.

post_text:
Governor Cuomo announced late this morning that NY PAUSE will be extended until May 15th, which includes schools. Our fantastic staff has been preparing for weeks in anticipation of this kind of announcement. We will continue to educate our students by any means possible. This week we started introducing new content to the students with the expectation that we focus on the essential skills we want our students to know. These procedures will remain in place until May 15th.

There has been no official announcement by the New York State Public High School Athletic Association regarding sports.

Through these tough times, we have already showed that this community stands together and cannot be broken. We will get through this!
#cgstrong

post_text:
We now have a Verizon hotspot located at the Howard Fire Hall for our residents on the Howard side of our district. The spot is located towards the back of the building with the password on the window.

There are now 3 locations where you can drive to get Wi-Fi service:

- CG High School next to the Superintendent's Office
- Greenwood School
- Howard Fire Hall

**As we determine where to place our 2 remaining hotspots, there are a few things we must consider.
- there must be good Verizon cell service in the area. If there is no cell service or bad service, we cannot place the hotspot there.
- we are attempting to hit the exterior regions of the district equitably. With only 4 hotspots total, we will do the best we can for our families that do not have internet to have a place close where they can go.
- unfortunately, we will not be able to provide service to all areas.

Thank you for your understanding.

Governor Cuomo announced today that New York schools are to remain closed until April 29th. The Canisteo-Greenwood School District will remain closed until April 29th under the Governor's Executive Order.

We will continue to provide food to our families and we will be reaching out later this week to introduce the next phase of our educational plan to our students and their families. Please be on the lookout for an email and Facebook post soon that will provide the details of what we are calling "Phase 2" of the closure.

Stay safe and stay healthy.

post_text:
Hello 1st Grade families!
We wanted to let you know that our class website is up and running! We haven’t ever made a website before, but we tried our best! A few things we wanted you to be aware of are the Weekly At-Home Schedule Ideas for Families and our Daily Scavenger Hunt. We also have resources for reading, math, writing, tricky words, crafts, story time, exercise, science, and computers.

Weekly At-Home Schedule Ideas for Families: https://www.cgcsd.org/Page/2833
• These are ideas that you are welcome to use any way you would like!
• The schedule is broken down into 15 minute blocks to help keep little ones focused on tasks.

Daily Scavenger Hunt: https://www.cgcsd.org/Page/2796#calendar3811/20200330/month
• Once you complete the scavenger hunt you can leave a message about what you found!

Remember, you are welcome to contact us via email if there is anything we can do to help support you!
Mrs. Dineen: ndineen@cgcsd.org
Mrs. Updyke: jupdyke@cgcsd.org

Mrs. Dineen & Mrs. Updyke
1st Grade Teachers

Today, CGES teacher, Miss Hillman started a YouTube channel to engage and encourage kids during the current closure due to COVID-19.

In her educational videos, she will be reading chapter books and providing activities for kids to do that has to do with what has been read.

Today, Miss Hillman posted her first chapter and activity. Moving forward, she will be (hopefully) posting every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. She is encouraging others to “Feel free to share” and “THIS IS GREAT FOR ALL AGES!!!”

She also shared, “Depending on how many kids get involved and actually watch these, I might do more fun things than just story reading. Any ideas? Send them to me, I’m open to anything to get these kids engaged!”

Way to go Miss Hillman. Keep up the great work!

https://youtu.be/edUxVua_bwo

A huge shout out to our amazing Canisteo-Greenwood Community and Jill May at Valley Apparel & Designs! In less than 24 hours, community members raised enough money via a Facebook campaign to purchase these fun Senior 2020 shirts for every member of the CG Senior Class! Valley Apparel & Design is printing and mailing the shirts to the seniors with no profit to their business!

Thank you to everyone who donated & Valley Apparel & Designs!

SENIORS, TO RECEIVE YOUR FREE T-SHIRT: If you haven't already done so, please email CGClassof2020@gmail.com with 1) Your name, 2) Your current mailing address and 3) Your shirt size. Once everyone has done this shirts can be ordered & printed.

post_text:
Quick Internet Access solution:

If you are in need of internet and do not have it at home; on the business office side of the CG High school we have moved our Wi-Fi access points to the outside walls. If you pull into any parking spot along the Business Office and Superintendent Office side of the building, you should be able to gain access. Pull up, log in, download work, watch a video, or participate in an on-line session.

Long-Term:

We are waiting to hear back from Verizon Wireless Govt. IF we are able to purchase hot-spots (hot commodity right now) , we will be placing them strategically throughout the district in CG transportation vehicles where you could pull along side the vehicle, connect to the hot-spot and get what you need. If we can purchase, they would be here around the end of March. We will keep you posted as this option develops.
UPDATE: WE WERE ABLE TO PURCHASE HOTSPOTS. THEY WILL BE HERE ASAP. ONCE THEY HAVE ARRIVED, WE WILL LET YOU KNOW WHERE WE WILL "PARK" THEM.

post_text:
Dear Families,
This message is to notify you that we are working in partnership with our county's Child Care Resource & Referral (CCR&R) agency, which has updated information about available healthcare during school closures related to COVID-19. The CCR&Rs will provide information on childcare providers to any parents seeking it and will provide enhanced referrals for all "essential employees". Enhanced referrals will include facilitating the process of finding an available slot so that parents in these crucial service professions have less legwork to do. To access this service, please contact the CCR&R from the list below that servers the county WHERE YOU LIVE.
- Accord Child Care Services (Allegany, Cattaraugus, Wyoming) 585-268-7605
- Chemung County Child Care Council - 607-734-3941
- Childcare Aware (Steuben, Schuyler) - 776-2126 ext. 236
- Family Enrichment Network (Broome, Chenango, Tioga) - 723-8313

We would like to take this moment to thank all of our essential employees for your dedication to your communities during this unprecedented time.

Food pick-up begins TODAY from 10am - 12pm at the Canisteo-Greenwood Elementary School and the Greenwood School. Drive up to the pop-up tent, tell them how many children you have in your home and we will give you what you need (you can stay right in your vehicle). For ease of transporting the food home, please bring a bag, box, laundry basket, etc. Pick-up will continue Monday - Friday until April 3rd.

Delivery starts tomorrow. Due to resources and food supply, we will not be able to deliver an entire week's of food as originally communicated. Next week, we will be delivering on Mondays and Wednesdays.

We would like to take this opportunity to thank the cafeteria workers and bus drivers that have spent countless hours preparing to feed our children, and getting ready to deliver to the families that need it.

post_text:
We have finalized of our plan to feed our students during the Steuben County Public Health Department mandated dismissal of students from March 18th to April 13th.

Starting this Wednesday, March 18th we will have the following provisions for food:

Residents with children will be able to pick up food daily (M-F) from 10am - 12pm at the Canisteo-Greenwood Elementary School and the Greenwood School. It will be a drive-thru style pick up where you will be able to drive up to an area outside the buildings (look for pop-up tents) and a staff member will give you the food you need for the day (breakfast and lunch) per child in your household. If you are unable to make any of the pick up points due to a transportation hardship, please let the offices know either tomorrow or Tuesday. We will be making deliveries to those families with transportation hardships on Thursdays, bringing an entire week of food to you at that time. The food pick-ups and delivery will be available until April 3rd.

We will keep you updated as needed.

At 1pm, the Steuben County Public Health Department declared that all Steuben County students are dismissed from school from Wednesday, March 18th through Spring Break. We have responded to this order by the following:
- Monday, March 16th - ONLY CTE students and Alt Ed students are to report to school at their regular bus times. No other students will be in attendance.
-Monday, March 16th :Conference Day for all staff. Please report to the HS Auditorium at 8am
- Tuesday, March 17th - All students report so that teachers can discuss with their students the learning opportunities that will occur through the dismissal and students can pick up personal belongings and needed instructional materials.
- Students will be dismissed from school from March 18th - April 13th.
Other important information:
- Fitness Center is closed until further notice
- Spring sports are postponed until April 14th. There will be no practices or contests
- The district is working out a plan to feed our students. Information will be forthcoming.

post_text:
CG Announces Co-Athlete for the month of February!
Congratulation Braidon Woodward, Varsity Wrestling team and Liz Roach, Girls Varsity Basketball team.

Braidon is 43-3 on the season and 8-0 in February. Braidon helped lead his team to a Section V Class B2 championship and is a 2x NY State Qualifier. Braidon was selected as a Steuben County 1st Team All-Star and attended the NYS Wrestling Championships

Liz Roach led her team to a 17-3 regular season record. Liz has averaged 11.5 points per game, 14 rebounds and 2.6 assists per game. She has a chance to break 1000 rebounds in her career. Liz was named a Steuben County 1st Team All-Star and selected to play in the Section V Ronald McDonald All-Star game!

post_text: The Canisteo-Greenwood Central School District is proud to announce that starting this month, the Mobile Family Resource Center is OPEN in the Greenwood building. Sponsored and operated by ProAction, the resource center provides opportunities for families to build important social skills and participate in family-focused activities. The site will operate on Mondays with the schedule changing depending on what classes the site is offering. You can enter the building by the gymnasium. We will have the schedule posted on our website monthly as well as here on Facebook. The Mobile Family Resource Center is a initiative to bring programming that would normally be found in Bath and Hornell and bring them to rural areas. If you have any questions, please feel free to reach out to their coordinator Sarah Blencowe.

post_text: The Canisteo-Greenwood Athlete of the Month for December is 8th grader Lillian Mullen of the Girls Varsity Basketball team. Lillian has helped lead her team to a perfect 4-0 start to the season. She's averaging 19.5 points per game and currently ranked #1 in scoring in the league. She's also ranked 3rd in scoring in all of Class C, and 15th in all of Section V! She helped her team win the Geneseo Tournament and was named to the All-Tournament team. If you happen to see Lily, please congratulate her on a job well done! Congratulations!

post_text:
The Canisteo-Greenwood Co-Athletes of the Month for October are Evan Amidon of the Boys Varsity Soccer team and Liz Roach of the Girls Varsity Soccer team. Both Liz and Evan have been major contributors to their team's success so far this season. Evan has led his team on the defensive end to what has been arguably been the best season in school history for Boys Varsity Soccer. Evan was named Steuben County Player of the Year and well as a 1st Team League All-Star. Evan will compete in the Exceptional Senior Game on Nov. 11th at Houghton College.

Liz has been irreplaceable in her position on the team. She's recorded one goal as a defender, takes most of the corner kicks and sets the team up for goal opportunities. She's helped the defense record 2 shutouts in 6 games. Elizabeth was also named to the Steuben County Exceptional Senior team! Both Evan and Liz helped their respective teams secure 1st round Sectional victories. Congratulations and great job Evan and Liz!

C-G names Jaiden Weitzel Athlete of the Month-
Girls Varsity Track & Field
Jaiden has had a very impressive senior season. She was named Co-MVP of the Hornell Invitational as well as Girls MVP of the Wellsville Spring Day Invitational where she won two events and broke a Spring Day record. Jaiden helped lead her team to a consecutive County Championship and a Section V Class CC Championship. Jaiden is the current CG record holder in the Long Jump (17' 10.5"). She won an individual Sectional Title in the Long Jump and was apart of our Girls 4 x 100 M Relay team that won a Sectional Title! Jaiden placed 4th at the New York State Track and Field Championship! Great job Jaiden!

Canisteo-Greenwood HS Athletics
May 28, 2019 at 2:29 PM ·

Proud to announce that NYSPHSAA will be recognizing Canisteo-Greenwood as a "School of Distinction" for the 2018-2019 school year. In order to win this award, 100% of our varsity teams (fall, winter & spring) must have 75% of their rosters with a 90% GPA or higher. This is a major accomplishment for our student-athletes, coaches and teachers. Last year there were only 30 schools in all of New York State who won this award!

So once again congratulations to our varsity teams and coaches of the following sports:
Football,Boys Soccer, Girls Soccer, Girls Tennis, Fall Cheerleading, Boys Basketball, Girls Basketball, Wrestling, Swimming, Winter Cheerleading, Baseball, Softball, Golf, and Boys/Girls Track.

Athlete of the Month!!
The Canisteo-Greenwood Athlete of the Month for November is Justin Becker of the Varsity Football team. Justin led his team to a 2nd consecutive league championship, birth in the Section V Class D Semi-finals and a 6-3 record. Justin led his team with 862 yards rushing, scored 8 touchdowns, registered 49 tackles, 2 interceptions and broke up 8 passes. He also averaged 16 yards per punt return. Justin was named a LCAA Divison III All-Star and was chosen to play in the Eddie Meath Game, the All-Star game which features the best football players in Section V. The game is being played Sunday, November 18th at the University of Rochester (5:00 PM kick-off). If you see Justin around, please congratulate him on a job well done!

post_text: Thank you John Kucko for the awesome picture of our Living Sign.
shared_text:
John Kucko Digital
October 9, 2018 at 8:47 AM ·

Canisteo Living Sign: Early traces of autumn color begin to emerge around the iconic “Canisteo Sign” in the Southern Tier. There since 1933, the sign would serve as a navigational visual back in the day (still does, I imagine). The sign is made from 260 pine trees spelling the name of the village. It’s about 90 feet long, 300 feet wide. It was placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2004. Thanks to one of my followers, John Babbitt, for the heads up on this, I never knew it existed—I’ll be back soon to get the complete fall shot.

post_text:
Parent Notice regarding Late Arrival Mondays.
We would like to inform parents of a significant change in the weekly calendars for the 2018-19 School Year. Late Arrival Mondays, aka PLC (Professional Learning Community) Mondays will no longer take place Monday mornings which has required many parents to find child care for their school aged child. Time has been carved out of the school day and after the school day ends providing teaching staff opportunities to write curriculum, co-plan, and collaborate as interdisciplinary teams. Buses will run at their regularly scheduled times Monday thru Friday throughout the school year. Please Share!!!

post_text:
The National Weather Service in Binghamton has issued a wind chill warning from 10 pm Thursday night through Sunday morning, wind chill warning means the combination of very cold air and the wind will create dangerously low wind chill values.

As with any severe weather Canisteo-Greenwood School District will be closely monitoring the forecast and conditions and, if a school closing or delay is deemed necessary, the school district will alert families as early as possible. The decision to send children to school ultimately rests with parents and guardians, and Canisteo-Greenwood will honor any family decision to keep children home because of inclement weather.

Important announcement regarding tonight’s graduation ceremony.

Due to the weather forecast, we are planning to have graduation at 7 pm indoors in the Elementary/Middle School gymnasium. If the forecast changes and it looks like we could go outside, we are prepared to shift the ceremony to the lighted football field.

With an indoor ceremony, seating will be first come/first served other than the reserved handicap seats we are already aware of. Doors to the school will open at 6 pm. There should be seating enough to accommodate everyone.

Additionally, tonight’s graduation ceremony if held indoors will be live streamed on the schools web page. www.cgcsd.org

We appreciate your flexibility as we wait on the weather.

post_text:
Canisteo-Greenwood School is now accepting nominations for Distinguished Friend of Canisteo-Greenwood.

The purpose of this award is to recognize an individual who has in some way significantly impacted the educational experiences of students in the Canisteo, Greenwood or Canisteo-Greenwood School Districts in years past. If you are aware of an individual that you strongly feel merits this distinguished recognition, please fill out the application on our website and provide the committee with a snapshot of the individual’s influence. In addition, feel free to include any additional documentation and references that will further assist the committee in understanding the scope of the individual’s accomplishments. Nominations need to be returned to the Canisteo-Greenwood District Clerk by January 31.
Thank You.
text:
Canisteo-Greenwood School is now accepting nominations for Distinguished Friend of Canisteo-Greenwood.

The purpose of this award is to recognize an individual who has in some way significantly impacted the educational experiences of students in the Canisteo, Greenwood or Canisteo-Greenwood School Districts in years past. If you are aware of an individual that you strongly feel merits this distinguished recognition, please fill out the application on our website and provide the committee with a snapshot of the individual’s influence. In addition, feel free to include any additional documentation and references that will further assist the committee in understanding the scope of the individual’s accomplishments. Nominations need to be returned to the Canisteo-Greenwood District Clerk by January 31.
Thank You.

Congratulations!!
All Varsity fall sports teams qualified for the Scholar Athlete Award.
Varsity Football, Boys Soccer, Girls Soccer, Cross Country, Volleyball and Tennis.

TEAM SCHOLAR ATHLETE AWARD CRITERIA:
In order for a team to be considered a SCHOLAR ATHLETE TEAM, they must encompass the following CRITERIA:
1. The team’s TOTAL Grade Point Average for 75% of the ROSTER must be 90.00 or above.
CONGRATULATIONS TEAMS!!!!

post_text: Throughout the school year the district conducts emergency drills with our staff and students. On Friday October 14th the Elementary/Middle School will be conducting a variety of safety drills. This will include lockdown drills and fire drills. As a reminder that during lockdown drills, our school will be closed to all visitors, until the drill is over. Your child in the elementary/middle school received a letter to bring home tonight explaining the safety drills. The day will end with students being dismissed 15 minutes earlier as part of the state wide Emergency Early Release Drill. After the drills on Friday, advanced notice of such drills will not be made public as a way to prepare for unexpected situations. Thank you for your assistance.
